research/history/memory.json:373:        "\u5982\u679c topk@EF1,K248 \u4ecd\u6709\u53ef\u89c1\u6539\u5584\u4e14\u8fd0\u884c\u4ee3\u4ef7\u7a33\u5b9a\uff0c\u5219\u53ef\u518d\u8865\u4e00\u4e2a\u8d34\u8fd1 0.5x \u7684\u7ec8\u70b9\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:380:    "whitened_topk": {
research/history/memory.json:382:      "design_hypothesis": "With the `topk` mainline saturated for five rounds, the highest-value matched architecture probe is a directly compatible near-neighbor that changes support formation without changing the exported reconstruction form. `whitened_topk` keeps the same `K=128` sparse weighted-sum decoder contract as `topk` but adds input preconditioning before top-k competition, so this round asks one clean question: does that architectural change alone produce a meaningfully better curve or enough promise to justify follow-up work.",
research/history/memory.json:395:        "If `whitened_topk` is clearly worse than the stabilized `topk` control, archive it immediately and return to mainline topk recipe work next round.",
research/history/memory.json:396:        "If `whitened_topk` is roughly competitive with a smoother or still-descending curve, record it as a promising probe result but still return to the topk mainline next round per policy.",
research/history/memory.json:397:        "If `whitened_topk` beats the matched topk control, schedule exactly one later follow-up on the same family after the mandated return to the mainline."
research/history/memory.json:405:      "design_hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 probe family \u7684\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff1b\u5176\u4e2d {b_i} \u662f\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5b57\u5178\u5e93\u4e2d\u7684\u56fa\u5b9a\u5411\u91cf\uff0calpha_i \u662f\u7ecf gate \u8c03\u5236\u540e\u7684\u5728\u7ebf\u7a00\u758f\u7cfb\u6570\u3002gate \u53ea\u6539\u53d8\u9009\u62e9\u4e0e\u7cfb\u6570\u8ba1\u7b97\u8def\u5f84\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u5355\u5e93\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u76f4\u63a5\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u201c\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u201d\u63a8\u7406\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u4e3b\u5047\u8bbe\uff1a\u5728\u4fdd\u6301 K=128\u3001EXPANSION_FACTOR=2\u3001OPTIMIZER=signum\u3001LR=3.0e-3 \u5b8c\u5168 matched \u7684\u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\uff0cgated \u662f\u5426\u80fd\u5728\u4ecd\u6ee1\u8db3\u9009\u62e9\u6210\u672c\u9884\u7b97\uff08EF=2 \u4e0b\u7ea6 1.0x h\u00d7n\uff09\u7684\u60c5\u51b5\u4e0b\uff0c\u76f8\u6bd4 topk \u63d0\u4f9b\u66f4\u597d\u7684 FVU\uff1b\u82e5\u5b83\u4ecd\u660e\u663e\u843d\u540e\u4e8e lowrank_residual / lowrank_soft_codebook_residual\uff0c\u5219\u8bf4\u660e\u7eaf\u5355\u5e93 gated \u8def\u7ebf\u5728\u5f53\u524d\u4f4e EF regime \u4e0b\u4e5f\u4e0d\u503c\u5f97\u7ee7\u7eed\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:572:        "\u82e5 gated \u4ecd\u660e\u663e\u52a3\u4e8e lowrank_residual / lowrank_soft_codebook_residual\uff0c\u5219\u4e0b\u4e00\u8f6e\u56de\u5230\u4e3b\u7ebf\uff0c\u53ea\u8c03\u4e00\u4e2a\u6210\u672c\u8f74\u5982 TRUNK_RANK\u3001NUM_CODES \u6216 STAGE1_RATIO\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:573:        "\u82e5 gated \u76f8\u6bd4 topk \u6709\u7a33\u5b9a\u6536\u76ca\u4f46\u4ecd\u8fdc\u900a\u4e8e low-rank family\uff0c\u53ef\u5c06 gate \u53ea\u89c6\u4e3a selector-side \u5c40\u90e8\u6280\u5de7\uff0c\u800c\u975e\u4e3b\u7ebf\u5019\u9009\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:574:        "\u7ee7\u7eed\u907f\u514d routed \u4e0e bucketed matched probe\uff0c\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u4eec\u5728 EF=2 \u4e0b selection_cost \u8d85\u8fc7 1.5\u00d7h\u00d7n \u9884\u7b97\u3002"
research/history/memory.json:580:    "factorized_topk": {
research/history/memory.json:582:      "design_hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: factorized_topk\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {b_i} \u6765\u81ea\u5355\u4e2a\u9759\u6001\u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1b\u4f4e\u79e9 factorized scorer \u53ea\u5f71\u54cd\u5728\u7ebf\u6253\u5206\u4e0e\u9009\u5740\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u4ecd\u662f\u5355\u5e93\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u76f4\u63a5\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u5355\u5e93\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u3002r214-r218 \u5df2\u8868\u660e topk@EF1 \u6cbf K \u8f74\u7ee7\u7eed\u52a0\u9884\u7b97\u4ecd\u80fd\u6539\u5584 FVU\uff0c\u4f46\u6700\u8fd1\u4e24\u8f6e\u6536\u76ca\u5df2\u660e\u663e\u53d8\u5c0f\u4e14\u603b\u8017\u65f6\u4e0a\u5347\u5230 417s\uff0c\u8bf4\u660e\u5355\u7eaf\u5806 topk \u67e5\u8868\u9884\u7b97\u63a5\u8fd1\u8fb9\u9645\u6536\u76ca\u6781\u9650\uff1b\u672c\u8f6e\u56e0\u6b64\u5207\u5230\u66f4\u4f4e encoder \u6210\u672c\u7684 factorized_topk\uff0c\u5e76\u628a K \u63d0\u5230 EF=1 \u4e0b\u7684\u6ee1\u5b57\u5178 256\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u662f\u5426\u80fd\u5728\u603b\u6210\u672c\u4ecd\u9884\u8ba1\u7ea6 0.44x\u3001\u7ee7\u7eed\u4f4d\u4e8e <0.5x \u533a\u57df\u7684\u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\uff0c\u7528\u66f4\u4fbf\u5b9c\u7684 selector \u6362\u53d6\u66f4\u9ad8\u53ef\u7528 K\uff0c\u4ece\u800c\u62ff\u5230\u63a5\u8fd1\u6216\u4f18\u4e8e topk@0.49x \u7684\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500 FVU\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:643:        "\u5982\u679c factorized_topk@EF1,K256 \u5728 <0.5x \u5185\u63a5\u8fd1\u6216\u4f18\u4e8e topk@K248 \u7684 FVU\uff0c\u8bf4\u660e\u4f4e\u79e9 scorer \u8def\u7ebf\u5728\u6781\u4f4e EF \u4e0b\u4ecd\u503c\u5f97\u4fdd\u7559\uff0c\u53ef\u7ee7\u7eed\u56f4\u7ed5\u8be5 family \u505a\u4f4e\u6210\u672c\u8865\u70b9\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:644:        "\u5982\u679c factorized_topk@EF1,K256 \u4ecd\u660e\u663e\u843d\u540e\u4e8e topk\uff0c\u8bf4\u660e\u5f53\u524d\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500\u533a\u7684\u5173\u952e\u4e0d\u5728 selector \u964d\u672c\u800c\u5728\u8868\u793a\u672c\u8eab\uff0c\u540e\u7eed\u5e94\u8f6c\u5411\u5176\u4ed6\u517c\u5bb9 family \u800c\u4e0d\u662f\u7ee7\u7eed\u8ffd factorized scorer\u3002"
research/history/memory.json:652:      "design_hypothesis": "Round 75 closed the simplest single-stage `topk` alternative: under the matched `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3` recipe it was clearly worse than the `two_stage_residual` mainline, so the next and only remaining high-value matched architecture probe this round should target a different deployment tradeoff rather than another plain top-k variant. `jumprelu` is the best single yes/no probe because it preserves LUTurbo's static-library finite weighted-sum form while potentially reducing online selection complexity through thresholded support shaping instead of a full staged residual path. This round asks one question only: under the exact current mainline recipe, is `jumprelu` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to remain worth later consideration, or should it be ruled out as clearly inferior?",
research/history/memory.json:673:        "If matched `jumprelu` is reasonably close with a healthy curve, return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round but keep one later `jumprelu` revisit available because its selector path may be cheaper to deploy.",
research/history/memory.json:674:        "If matched `jumprelu` is clearly worse than `two_stage_residual` across the curve, close the probe and return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round.",
research/history/memory.json:675:        "If matched `jumprelu` unexpectedly beats the current `two_stage_residual` reference, still return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round per policy, but record `jumprelu` as a high-priority later follow-up family."
research/history/memory.json:681:    "routed": {
research/history/memory.json:683:      "design_hypothesis": "Round 60 showed that matched `jumprelu` is competitive enough to avoid immediate dismissal but still clearly trails the strengthened `gated` anchor (`0.148243` vs `0.142923`), so the next single architecture question should test the closest support-selection near-neighbor rather than another looser variant. `routed` preserves LUTurbo's static-vector finite weighted-sum reconstruction contract while separating support routing from activation magnitude, so this round asks one clean yes/no question: under the exact current mainline recipe (`K=128`, `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`), is `routed` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to justify any later follow-up as a deployment-relevant family?",
research/history/memory.json:696:        "If matched `routed` is clearly worse than the strengthened `gated` anchor, return to the `gated` mainline next round and close this probe.",
research/history/memory.json:697:        "If matched `routed` is roughly competitive with a healthy curve, still return to the `gated` mainline next round, but preserve one later revisit because decoupled routing may better align with LUTurbo online-cost goals.",
research/history/memory.json:698:        "If matched `routed` unexpectedly beats the current `gated` anchor, return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy but schedule exactly one later follow-up for this family."
research/history/memory.json:704:    "group_topk": {
research/history/memory.json:706:      "design_hypothesis": "With the `gated` mainline stalled for nine rounds, the highest-value Round 62 matched architecture probe is `group_topk`: it preserves the same static decoder-library weighted-sum export contract and fixed `K=128`, while changing only support formation to a group-local winner scheme that could reduce selection complexity if reconstruction stays competitive. This probe answers one question only: is `group_topk` intrinsically strong enough under the matched `signum`/`2.0e-3`/`EF=12` recipe to merit any later follow-up.",
research/history/memory.json:719:        "If `group_topk` is clearly worse than matched `gated` at `K=128`, discard the family and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
research/history/memory.json:720:        "If `group_topk` is roughly competitive, record it as a potentially deployment-friendlier selector but still return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy.",
research/history/memory.json:721:        "If `group_topk` unexpectedly beats matched `gated`, schedule at most one later follow-up after the mandated return to the `gated` mainline."
research/history/memory.json:727:    "bucketed_topk": {
research/history/memory.json:729:      "design_hypothesis": "With the `gated` mainline now stalled for ten rounds and `group_topk` already coming back slightly but clearly worse, the next highest-value matched architecture probe is `bucketed_topk`: it preserves the same fixed-`K` static weighted-sum decoder contract while changing only the selector architecture to a simple input-conditioned bucket specialization. This round answers one question only: under the matched `K=128`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EF=12` recipe, is `bucketed_topk` intrinsically strong enough to justify any later follow-up, or should it be ruled out immediately.",
research/history/memory.json:742:        "If `bucketed_topk` is clearly worse than matched `gated`, discard the family and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
research/history/memory.json:743:        "If `bucketed_topk` is roughly competitive, record it as a possible selector-specialization direction but still return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy.",
research/history/memory.json:744:        "If `bucketed_topk` unexpectedly beats matched `gated`, schedule at most one later follow-up after the mandated return to the `gated` mainline."
research/history/memory.json:750:    "codebook_topk": {
research/history/memory.json:752:      "design_hypothesis": "Rounds 75 and 76 ruled out the simplest matched single-stage alternatives under the current `two_stage_residual` anchor: both `topk` and `jumprelu` were clearly worse at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3`. The next single matched architecture probe should therefore test a structurally different exportable decomposition rather than another plain selector. `codebook_topk` is the highest-value remaining yes/no probe because it still maps to a finite weighted sum over static vector libraries, but may reduce LUTurbo online coefficient and lookup cost by reusing a compact static basis instead of a full staged residual path. This round asks one question only: under the exact current mainline recipe, is `codebook_topk` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to remain worth later consideration, or should it be ruled out as clearly inferior to `two_stage_residual`?",
research/history/memory.json:773:        "If matched `codebook_topk` is reasonably close with a healthy curve, return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round but keep one later `codebook_topk` revisit available because its shared-codebook path may be cheaper to deploy.",
research/history/memory.json:774:        "If matched `codebook_topk` is clearly worse than `two_stage_residual` across the curve, close the probe and return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round.",
research/history/memory.json:775:        "If matched `codebook_topk` unexpectedly beats the current `two_stage_residual` reference, still return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round per policy, but record `codebook_topk` as a high-priority later follow-up family."
research/history/memory.json:781:    "two_stage_residual": {
research/history/memory.json:783:      "design_hypothesis": "Round 73 answered the optimizer question clearly: `adam` on the `two_stage_residual` reference recipe failed catastrophically (`FVU=33.8917`), so the optimizer branch should be considered closed and `signum` remains the correct mainline optimizer for this family. Following the prescribed order, the next single mainline question is now loss shaping: with `ARCHITECTURE=two_stage_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3` fixed, is the default auxiliary loss helping this staged residual decomposition, or does removing it improve the full training trajectory and final FVU?",
research/history/memory.json:836:        "If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` improves the `two_stage_residual` curve or endpoint, keep loss-side tuning alive with at most one nearby confirmation.",
research/history/memory.json:844:    "lowrank_two_stage_residual": {
research/history/memory.json:846:      "design_hypothesis": "`adam` at the exact `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor failed catastrophically, so the optimizer question is now cleanly resolved in favor of `signum`. The next single question should move to the loss axis rather than K or another architecture change: dropping `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.03125` to `0.0` tests whether the current mainline is being mildly over-regularized and whether a cleaner reconstruction objective improves the mid/late training curve under the settled `signum` recipe.",
research/history/memory.json:907:    "routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual": {
research/history/memory.json:909:      "design_hypothesis": "`lowrank_two_stage_residual` has now had its K128 signum recipe mostly clarified, and the operator allows exactly one matched architecture probe. The highest-value single probe is `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual`: it preserves the same low-rank staged static-library decomposition while changing only the support-selection mechanism. If routing cannot beat or closely pressure the current `lowrank_two_stage_residual` anchor under the exact same `K=128, EF=12, signum, LR=2.0e-3` recipe, then this extra routing complexity is not worth continuing in the current LUTurbo-aligned regime.",
research/history/memory.json:922:        "Return to the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline next round regardless, per the operator instruction.",
research/history/memory.json:923:        "If `routed_lowrank_two_stage_residual` is clearly worse or less stable, keep focus on mainline loss/preprocess clarification rather than reopening routed variants.",
research/history/memory.json:930:    "lowrank_residual_vq": {
research/history/memory.json:932:      "design_hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_residual_vq` under the unchanged mainline recipe (`K=128, EF=2, signum, lr=3.0e-3`). Final reconstruction is `x_hat = U(Vx) + c_m + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk library, `c_m` is one selected codebook vector from a static coarse library, and the residual term is a weighted sum over a static residual dictionary. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9` because LUTurbo/Lottable can export the trunk factors, coarse codebook, and residual dictionary as static vector libraries, then run `trunk branch + coarse code lookup + sparse residual lookups + weighted sum` online. The single question for this probe is whether replacing the soft coarse branch with a hard VQ-style coarse branch is worth continuing in the low-EF feasible regime. This should stay inside the encoder-cost budget at `EF=2`, so it is likely to produce a real training/runtime signal rather than another policy reject.",
research/history/memory.json:953:        "Return to the mainline `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` next round and tune exactly one cost knob such as `TRUNK_RANK`, `NUM_CODES`, or `STAGE1_RATIO`.",
research/history/memory.json:954:        "If `lowrank_residual_vq` underperforms the mainline on FVU or slows training without a compensating runtime/quality benefit, mark hard-VQ coarse branches as not worth continuing in the current low-cost regime."
research/history/memory.json:991:        "Return to the mainline `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` next round and tune exactly one cost knob such as `TRUNK_RANK`, `NUM_CODES`, or `STAGE1_RATIO`.",
research/history/memory.json:1000:      "design_hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 probe family \u7684\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff1b\u5176\u4e2d low-rank trunk \u9879 U(Vx) \u53ef\u5bfc\u51fa\u4e3a\u9759\u6001 trunk \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\u4e0a\u7684\u52a0\u6743\u548c\uff0cresidual \u5206\u652f \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i \u53ef\u5bfc\u51fa\u4e3a\u9759\u6001 residual \u5b57\u5178\u4e0a\u7684\u7a00\u758f\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u3002gated selector \u53ea\u6539\u53d8\u5728\u7ebf\u9009\u62e9\u4e0e\u7cfb\u6570\u8c03\u5236\u8def\u5f84\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u80fd\u591f\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u201c\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u201d\u63a8\u7406\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u4e3b\u5047\u8bbe\uff1a\u5728\u4fdd\u6301 K=128\u3001EXPANSION_FACTOR=2\u3001OPTIMIZER=signum\u3001LR=3.0e-3 \u5b8c\u5168 matched \u7684\u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\uff0clowrank_gated_residual \u662f\u5426\u80fd\u5728\u4ecd\u6ee1\u8db3\u9009\u62e9\u6210\u672c\u9884\u7b97\u7684\u60c5\u51b5\u4e0b\uff0c\u76f8\u6bd4 plain lowrank_residual \u63d0\u4f9b\u66f4\u597d\u7684 FVU\uff1b\u82e5\u5b83\u4ecd\u660e\u663e\u843d\u540e\u4e8e lowrank_soft_codebook_residual \u4e0e\u4e3b\u7ebf\uff0c\u5219\u8bf4\u660e gate \u4f5c\u4e3a residual-side selector \u6539\u9020\u5728\u5f53\u524d\u4f4e EF regime \u4e0b\u4e0d\u503c\u5f97\u7ee7\u7eed\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1037:        "\u82e5 lowrank_gated_residual \u4ecd\u660e\u663e\u52a3\u4e8e lowrank_soft_codebook_residual\uff0c\u5219\u4e0b\u4e00\u8f6e\u56de\u5230\u4e3b\u7ebf\uff0c\u53ea\u8c03\u4e00\u4e2a\u6210\u672c\u8f74\u5982 TRUNK_RANK\u3001NUM_CODES \u6216 STAGE1_RATIO\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1038:        "\u82e5\u5b83\u4ec5\u5c0f\u5e45\u4f18\u4e8e lowrank_residual \u4f46\u8bad\u7ec3\u66f4\u6162\u6216\u9009\u62e9\u6210\u672c\u66f4\u9ad8\uff0c\u5219\u5c06 gating \u89c6\u4e3a\u8d1f\u9762\u4fe1\u53f7\uff0c\u4e0d\u518d\u7ee7\u7eed\u5360\u7528 probe \u8f6e\u6b21\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1039:        "\u7ee7\u7eed\u907f\u514d routed \u4e0e bucketed matched probe\uff0c\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u4eec\u5728 EF=2 \u4e0b selection_cost \u8d85\u8fc7 1.5\u00d7h\u00d7n \u9884\u7b97\u3002"
research/history/memory.json:1047:      "design_hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_grouped_residual` with `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=2`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=3.0e-3` fixed. Final reconstruction formula is `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk library and `{b_i}` is a static residual dictionary; grouped competition changes only how residual support is selected, not the exported decoder basis. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`: LUTurbo/Lottable can export it as one static trunk lookup plus one sparse weighted sum over a static residual library, so inference remains a finite weighted sum over fixed vector banks. At EF=2 its encoder selection cost should remain within the `\u2264 1.5\u00d7h\u00d7n` hard budget because it reuses the feasible `lowrank_residual` scorer stack and only constrains support selection. The single question is whether group-local residual competition is intrinsically worth keeping in the low-EF deployable regime, or whether even this cheaper selector simplification is clearly inferior to the current two-stage soft-codebook mainline.",
research/history/memory.json:1068:        "If `lowrank_grouped_residual` is clearly worse than the two-stage mainline in both FVU and runtime metrics, discard grouped low-rank residual variants and return to `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` next round.",
research/history/memory.json:1076:    "lowrank_residual": {
research/history/memory.json:1078:      "design_hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 probe family \u7684\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff1b\u5176\u4e2d low-rank trunk \u9879 U(Vx) \u53ef\u5bfc\u51fa\u4e3a\u9759\u6001 trunk \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\u4e0a\u7684\u52a0\u6743\u548c\uff0cresidual \u5206\u652f \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i \u53ef\u5bfc\u51fa\u4e3a\u9759\u6001 residual \u5b57\u5178\u4e0a\u7684\u7a00\u758f\u52a0\u6743\u548c\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u80fd\u591f\u843d\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u2018\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u2019\u63a8\u7406\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u4e3b\u5047\u8bbe\uff1a\u5728\u4fdd\u6301 K=128\u3001EXPANSION_FACTOR=2\u3001OPTIMIZER=signum\u3001LR=3.0e-3 \u5b8c\u5168 matched \u7684\u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\uff0c\u53bb\u6389 soft codebook coarse branch \u540e\uff0clowrank_residual \u662f\u5426\u4ecd\u503c\u5f97\u4f5c\u4e3a\u66f4\u4f4e encoder selection cost \u7684\u6781\u7b80\u517c\u5bb9\u652f\u7ebf\uff1b\u82e5 FVU \u76f8\u6bd4\u4e3b\u7ebf\u4e0e lowrank_soft_codebook_residual \u90fd\u660e\u663e\u6076\u5316\uff0c\u5219\u8bf4\u660e coarse codebook \u5206\u652f\u672c\u8eab\u662f\u5f53\u524d\u4e3b\u7ebf\u4e0d\u53ef\u7f3a\u5c11\u7684\u7ed3\u6784\u589e\u76ca\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1131:        "\u82e5 lowrank_residual \u660e\u663e\u52a3\u4e8e lowrank_soft_codebook_residual\uff0c\u5219\u4e0b\u4e00\u8f6e\u56de\u5230\u4e3b\u7ebf\uff0c\u53ea\u8c03\u4e00\u4e2a\u6210\u672c\u8f74\u5982 TRUNK_RANK\u3001NUM_CODES \u6216 STAGE1_RATIO\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1132:        "\u82e5 lowrank_residual \u5728\u66f4\u4f4e selection_cost \u4e0b\u4ecd\u4fdd\u6301\u53ef\u63a5\u53d7 FVU \u4e14\u8bad\u7ec3\u66f4\u5feb\uff0c\u53ef\u5c06\u5176\u4fdd\u7559\u4e3a\u66f4\u4f4e\u6210\u672c\u7684\u517c\u5bb9\u5907\u9009\u652f\u7ebf\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1133:        "\u7ee7\u7eed\u907f\u514d routed \u4e0e bucketed matched probe\uff0c\u56e0\u4e3a\u5b83\u4eec\u5728 EF=2 \u4e0b selection_cost \u8d85\u8fc7 1.5\u00d7h\u00d7n \u9884\u7b97\u3002"
research/history/memory.json:1139:    "whitened_lowrank_residual": {
research/history/memory.json:1141:      "design_hypothesis": "After the simpler low-rank single-stage selectors (`lowrank_residual`, `lowrank_gated_residual`, `lowrank_jumprelu_residual`, and `lowrank_grouped_residual`) all failed against the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor, the most informative remaining matched architecture probe is `whitened_lowrank_residual`. It keeps the same low-rank trunk and single-stage static-library residual decode, but changes only the residual conditioning before support selection. This answers a clean question: was the mainline gain coming from the second residual stage itself, or can a better-conditioned single-stage selector recover enough quality to be worth any further attention. If `whitened_lowrank_residual` is still clearly weaker under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, then the current evidence favors the two-stage residual mechanism rather than more single-stage low-rank variants.",
research/history/memory.json:1154:        "If `whitened_lowrank_residual` is clearly weaker than the matched `lowrank_two_stage_residual` anchor, discard it and resume mainline tuning on `lowrank_two_stage_residual` next round.",
research/history/memory.json:1155:        "If `whitened_lowrank_residual` is unexpectedly competitive at matched K128, record it as a single-stage comparison point but still return to the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline next round per probe policy."
research/history/memory.json:1163:      "design_hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: lowrank_factorized_residual\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_r beta_r u_r + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {u_r} \u662f\u9759\u6001 trunk \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff0c{b_i} \u662f\u9759\u6001 residual \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1b\u5728\u7ebf\u4fa7\u53ea\u8ba1\u7b97\u7cfb\u6570 beta_r \u4e0e alpha_i\uff0c\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u65f6\u53ef\u62c6\u6210 trunk \u5e93\u67e5\u8868\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u4e0e residual \u5e93\u67e5\u8868\u52a0\u6743\u548c\uff0c\u4e24\u90e8\u5206\u90fd\u6ee1\u8db3\u9759\u6001\u5411\u91cf\u5e93\u4e0a\u7684\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u57fa\u4e8e r210 \u5df2\u5728\u5f53\u524d family \u4e0a\u62ff\u5230 0.69x / 0.1256 \u4e14 tokens_per_sec \u7ea6 166.6k\u3001\u603b\u8017\u65f6 291s\uff0c\u5f53\u524d\u6700\u503c\u5f97\u56de\u7b54\u7684\u5355\u4e00\u95ee\u9898\u4e0d\u662f\u518d\u6362 family\uff0c\u800c\u662f\u8be5\u70b9\u7684\u9ad8\u6210\u672c\u662f\u5426\u4e3b\u8981\u7531 trunk \u8fc7\u5bbd\u5bfc\u81f4\uff1b\u672c\u8f6e\u4ec5\u5c06 TRUNK_RANK \u4e0b\u8c03\u5230 16\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u80fd\u5426\u5728\u4fdd\u6301\u660e\u663e\u4f18\u4e8e topk@0.31x \u7684 FVU \u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\uff0c\u628a total_cost \u5c3d\u91cf\u538b\u5411\u5e76\u6700\u597d\u538b\u5165 <0.5x \u533a\u57df\u3002",
research/history/memory.json:1202:        "\u5982\u679c TRUNK_RANK=16 \u8fdb\u5165 <0.5x \u4e14 FVU \u4ecd\u660e\u663e\u4f18\u4e8e topk@EF1,K64\uff0c\u5219\u56fa\u5b9a\u8be5 family \u540e\u53ea\u6cbf K \u8f74\u8865\u4e00\u4e2a\u70b9\u3002",
