research/history/round_summaries/round_0173.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual` with `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=2`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=3.0e-3` fixed. Final reconstruction formula is `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_m pi_m c_m + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk library, `{c_m}` is a static soft-codebook library, and `{b_i}` is a static residual dictionary; grouping changes only how the residual support is selected, not the exported decoder basis. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`: LUTurbo/Lottable can export it as one static trunk lookup plus one static codebook lookup plus one sparse weighted sum over a static residual library, so inference remains a finite weighted sum over fixed vector banks. At EF=2 its encoder selection cost should remain within the `\u2264 1.5\u00d7h\u00d7n` hard budget because it reuses the same feasible lowrank soft-codebook scorer stack and only constrains support selection. The single question is whether the soft-codebook branch remains worthwhile with cheaper group-local residual competition, or whether full global residual selection is still necessary.",
