research/history/round_summaries/round_0167.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0167.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` with `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=2`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=3.0e-3` fixed. Final reconstruction formula is `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_m \u03c0_m c_m + \u03a3_i \u03b1_i^(1) b_i + \u03a3_j \u03b1_j^(2) b_j`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk library, `{c_m}` is a static soft codebook library, and `{b_i}` is a static residual dictionary; only the stage budget split differs from the mainline. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9` because LUTurbo can export it as trunk lookup + codebook lookup + two sparse residual lookups over fixed libraries. The single question is whether front-loading the sparse budget is intrinsically worthwhile in the low-EF deployable regime, after keeping the whole matched recipe identical.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0167.json:20:    "summary": "Run one valid matched architecture probe on `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` with the mainline `K=128`, `EF=2`, `signum`, and `LR=3.0e-3` recipe explicitly pinned. This cleanly answers whether asymmetric stage allocation is worth any further attention in the current LUTurbo-compatible low-EF regime.",
