research/history/logs/agent_round_0040.stdout.log:84:research/history/results.tsv:40:r39_1774539654	1774539654	ok	keep	0.148156076669693	128	gated	12				/root/sparsify-ascend/checkpoints/research_agent/round_0039/round0039_standard_1774539084_dp2_bs1_ga8_ef12_k128_20260326_233130	583257da77822fd7781b4701d5d19f522c346304			Continue on the same `gated` mainline and probe only the learning-rate axis. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `OPTIMIZER=signum` fixed, explicitly pin the reference aux/runtime knobs, and raise `LR` from `1.6e-3` to `2.0e-3`. Read the whole curve, not just terminal FVU: if the higher LR preserves stability while improving mid-to-late descent below the refreshed `0.149936` control, then the current anchor was slightly conservative; if it becomes noisier or finishes worse, keep `1.6e-3` as the gated LR anchor and stop the LR branch.	This stays on the active family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one core variable: `lr`. It also follows the prescribed order now that the clean baseline has been backfilled successfully. The main risk is that `2.0e-3` could overdrive training, but the evidence so far points the other way: `1.2e-3` was clearly slower/worse, and the refreshed `1.6e-3` baseline was still improving late.	/root/sparsify-ascend/research/history/logs/round0039_standard_1774539084.log
