research/history/round_summaries/round_0065.json:19:    "hypothesis": "With the `gated` mainline stalled for twelve rounds and recent single-stage selector probes (`group_topk`, `bucketed_topk`, `codebook_topk`) all failing to beat it, the next highest-value matched architecture probe is `two_stage_residual`: it remains LUTurbo-compatible because the reconstruction is still a finite weighted sum over static libraries, but distributes the fixed `K=128` budget across two sequential residual passes. This round answers one question only: under the matched `signum`/`LR=2.0e-3`/`EF=12` recipe, is that staged residual decomposition intrinsically strong enough to justify any later follow-up, or should it be ruled out immediately.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0065.json:23:    "family_name": "two_stage_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0065.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0065.json:52:      "`two_stage_residual` is extended-compatible with LUTurbo because its final reconstruction can be exported as the sum of two fixed-size sparse weighted sums over static decoder libraries, with a fixed stage split of the total `K`.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0065.json:53:      "Judge this probe strictly as a family-worthiness test against matched `gated` K128: if it is clearly worse, discard it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, record the result but still return to the mainline per policy."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0065.json:56:      "If `two_stage_residual` is clearly worse than matched `gated`, discard the family and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
