research/history/round_summaries/round_0017.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 16 showed that `topk/signum/LR=1.6e-3/EF=12` at `K=32` did not collapse and still maintained a smooth late-stage FVU descent, so the next single question is whether LUTurbo can push cost one more notch lower before quality degradation becomes too steep. This round changes only `K`, moving from `32` to `24` while keeping the same family and recipe fixed, to measure the next deployable point on the low-K cost-quality frontier.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0017.json:23:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0017.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0017.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active mainline family, changes exactly one primary variable (`k`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the observed K-lane evidence. The main risk is that `K=32 -> 24` may cross the practical quality boundary, but the K32 curve still improved smoothly through the end, so a finer step to `24` is more defensible than jumping straight to `16`.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0017.json:53:      "For LUTurbo, this lane is valuable because it directly probes lower online selection and weighted-sum cost under a fixed export-compatible topk recipe."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0017.json:79:    "self_review": "This stays on the active mainline family, changes exactly one primary variable (`k`), respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and follows directly from the observed K-lane evidence. The main risk is that `K=32 -> 24` may cross the practical quality boundary, but the K32 curve still improved smoothly through the end, so a finer step to `24` is more defensible than jumping straight to `16`.",
research/history/logs/agent_action_0177.json:1:{"change_type":"param_only","command":"run","env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"2"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"3.0e-3"}],"expected_win":"explore_unknown","experiment_tier":"proxy","family_name":"routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"prototype","hypothesis":"Matched architecture probe on `routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` under the unchanged mainline recipe (`K=128, EF=2, signum, lr=3.0e-3`). Final reconstruction remains `x_hat = U(Vx) + Σ_m pi_m c_m + Σ_i alpha_i^(1) b_i + Σ_j alpha_j^(2) b_j`; routing only perturbs stage-1/stage-2 support selection scores, while all decoded terms still come from static trunk, codebook, and residual libraries. This is `扩展兼容` because LUTurbo/Lottable can export the low-rank trunk matrices, soft codebook vectors, and residual dictionary once, then execute `trunk lookup + codebook lookup + routed support selection + weighted sparse lookups + sum` online. The key question is whether router-driven support allocation is worth continuing in the low-EF feasible regime. Current cost accounting strongly suggests no: adding two full routers likely pushes encoder selection cost above the `1.5x h×n` hard cap, so the most informative outcome is a quick policy gate that rules this family out as a mainline candidate at `EF=2`.","needs_sanity":false,"next_hypotheses":["Return to the mainline `lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` next round and tune exactly one cost knob such as `TRUNK_RANK`, `NUM_CODES`, or `STAGE1_RATIO`.","If this routed matched probe is policy-rejected as expected, mark routed two-stage soft-codebook as not worth continuing in the current low-cost regime unless a future single-variable cost-reduction round explicitly targets router cost."],"notes_to_memory":["`routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` is LUTurbo `扩展兼容`: routing changes selector logic only; decode path is still a finite weighted sum over static trunk/codebook/residual libraries.","At matched `K=128, EF=2`, routed two-stage soft-codebook is expected to exceed the encoder-cost cap because the two router projections add substantial full-dictionary selection cost on top of the mainline scorer.","Treat a fast policy rejection here as a useful architectural conclusion, not a runtime failure: the family is exportable but not cost-viable in the current feasible regime."],"primary_variable":"architecture","self_review":"Single-variable discipline is preserved: only `ARCHITECTURE` changes, while `K`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, `OPTIMIZER`, and `LR` remain fixed to the mainline recipe. This probe is intentionally chosen to answer a clean architectural question under the new budget regime: whether routing is inherently worth carrying forward once low-EF cost feasibility is enforced.","summary":"Probe `routed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` as the one matched architecture change. It is LUTurbo-exportable (`扩展兼容`) by the same static-library decomposition as the mainline, but is likely to be ruled out quickly because the extra routers make encoder selection cost exceed the hard budget, which would mean this family is not worth continuing on the current Pareto frontier.","touched_files":[]}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0045.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 44 cleanly reproduced the Hadamard-enabled `gated` improvement at `K=128`, so that preprocess gain is now stable enough to treat as the operative recipe rather than a one-off. The next single question is therefore K transfer under the improved recipe: if we keep `gated`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EF=12`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1` fixed and step down only to `K=96`, does the stronger recipe preserve or extend `gated`'s advantage at the next lower support where online cost is meaningfully lower?","summary":"Adopt the reproduced Hadamard recipe as the current `gated` reference and begin K mapping under that stronger setting. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1` fixed, and change only `K` from `128` to `96`. Judge the run by the whole trajectory as well as the endpoint: if the improved recipe yields a smooth curve and clearly beats the old `gated@96` control (`0.168960`), then the preprocess gain transfers to a lower-cost point and the family deserves at least one more K step; if it falls back toward the earlier K96 result or loses its curve advantage, keep the improved recipe mainly as a K128 anchor.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_cost","family_name":"gated","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active `gated` family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one core variable: `k`. The clean Hadamard confirmation in Round 44 closes the recipe-clarification loop, so moving to K is now the most policy-clean next action. The main risk is that the K128 improvement may not transfer downward, but that is precisely the high-value deployment question this round answers.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"gated"},{"key":"K","value":"96"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"BATCH_SIZE","value":"1"},{"key":"GRAD_ACC_STEPS","value":"8"},{"key":"MICRO_ACC_STEPS","value":"1"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.03125"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"1"},{"key":"COMPILE_MODEL","value":"1"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Rounds 43 and 44 jointly established that `USE_HADAMARD=1` is a reproducible improvement for `gated@128` under `signum, LR=2.0e-3`, so this recipe is now stable enough to use for K mapping.","Round 45 transfers the improved `gated` recipe to `K=96` to test whether the K128 preprocess gain also buys a better lower-cost point rather than only improving the largest-support anchor."],"next_hypotheses":["If the improved `gated@96` run beats the old K96 control with a similarly healthy curve, continue down to `K=64` under the same recipe.","If `gated@96` fails to improve materially under the stronger recipe, treat the Hadamard gain as mostly a K128 effect and avoid a long downward K sweep without new evidence."],"primary_variable":"k"}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0064.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"With the `gated` mainline stalled for eleven rounds and the lighter selector probes `group_topk` and `bucketed_topk` both coming back clearly worse, the next highest-value matched architecture probe is `codebook_topk`: it remains LUTurbo-compatible because the reconstruction is still a finite sum over static libraries, but it changes the architecture by adding a hard coarse codebook selection before the sparse residual. This round answers one question only: under the matched `K=128`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EF=12` recipe, is `codebook_topk` intrinsically strong enough to justify any later follow-up, or should it be ruled out immediately.","summary":"Run one matched architecture probe by switching `ARCHITECTURE` from `gated` to `codebook_topk` while keeping `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"explore_unknown","family_name":"codebook_topk","family_stage":"prototype","self_review":"This obeys the Round 64 policy by changing exactly one primary variable: architecture. `codebook_topk` is a better remaining probe than batch-coupled variants because it stays single-sample deployable, and it is more informative than heavier multi-branch gating because it tests a distinct static-library decomposition pattern that could plausibly trade some sparse support work for a coarse lookup plus residual correction.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"codebook_topk"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 64 spends the single allowed matched architecture probe on `codebook_topk` after `group_topk` and `bucketed_topk` both failed to beat the matched `gated` control.","`codebook_topk` is extended-compatible with LUTurbo because the final reconstruction can be exported as a hard-selected static coarse codebook vector plus a finite weighted sum over a static residual decoder library.","Judge this probe strictly as a family-worthiness test against matched `gated` K128: if it is clearly worse, discard it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, record the result but still return to the mainline per policy."],"next_hypotheses":["If `codebook_topk` is clearly worse than matched `gated`, discard the family and return to the `gated` mainline next round.","If `codebook_topk` is roughly competitive, record it as a possible coarse-plus-residual deployment direction but still return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy.","If `codebook_topk` unexpectedly beats matched `gated`, schedule at most one later follow-up after the mandated return to the `gated` mainline."],"primary_variable":"architecture"}
