research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:20:    "summary": "Round 36 changed the picture: `gated@96` is not just viable, it improved the frontier over the existing `topk@96` control, so the family has earned one more K-mapping round. Keep the anchored recipe fixed and step only `K` from `96` to `64`. This directly answers whether the `gated` advantage generalizes to the next adjacent frontier point. Read the full curve, not just the endpoint: if training remains smooth and finishes below the `topk@64` control (`0.1992608`), `gated` is a real high-K mainline candidate; if it drops back behind `topk`, then the family likely helps only in the upper-K regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the current family, keeps EF fixed at 12, and changes exactly one main variable: `K`. It follows the prescribed ordering because recipe tuning was already exhausted before K moves began, and `K=64` is the highest-value next probe after the successful `K=96` result.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:55:      "If `gated@64` also beats `topk@64`, continue one more downward K probe because gated is shaping up as the stronger mainline family across multiple frontier points.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:76:    "description": "Round 36 changed the picture: `gated@96` is not just viable, it improved the frontier over the existing `topk@96` control, so the family has earned one more K-mapping round. Keep the anchored recipe fixed and step only `K` from `96` to `64`. This directly answers whether the `gated` advantage generalizes to the next adjacent frontier point. Read the full curve, not just the endpoint: if training remains smooth and finishes below the `topk@64` control (`0.1992608`), `gated` is a real high-K mainline candidate; if it drops back behind `topk`, then the family likely helps only in the upper-K regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0037.json:77:    "self_review": "This stays on the current family, keeps EF fixed at 12, and changes exactly one main variable: `K`. It follows the prescribed ordering because recipe tuning was already exhausted before K moves began, and `K=64` is the highest-value next probe after the successful `K=96` result.",
research/history/logs/agent_action_0103.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Rounds 101 and 102 showed that the controller still treats `ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual K=128 EXPANSION_FACTOR=12 OPTIMIZER=signum LR=2.0e-3` as the official mainline reference recipe for single-axis comparisons, so the cleanest next question is optimizer choice at that exact anchor. Switching only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam` while holding the reference `LR=2.0e-3` fixed tests whether this family has any optimizer headroom before spending another round on an optimizer-local LR callback, and it should be judged by the full curve shape against the signum reference rather than only the terminal FVU.","summary":"Stay on the `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` mainline and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`, while keeping `ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=2.0e-3` fixed.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"lower_fvu","family_name":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This corrects the last two policy rejects by anchoring the optimizer comparison to the controller-declared reference recipe instead of the unofficial `LR=2.4e-3` signum probe. Only one primary variable changes, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` remains explicit, and the result will cleanly answer whether `adam` deserves exactly one follow-up LR callback in this family.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"adam"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 103 re-asks the optimizer question on the controller's official mainline reference recipe after Rounds 101 and 102 were policy-rejected for effectively coupling optimizer selection with a non-reference LR.","Judge this run by the whole trajectory versus the archived signum reference at `K=128`, `EF=12`, `LR=2.0e-3`, especially early stability and mid/late descent shape.","Only if `adam` is competitive on this matched reference should it earn one optimizer-local LR callback next; otherwise keep `signum` and move on."],"next_hypotheses":["If `adam` is competitive with or better than matched `signum` at `LR=2.0e-3`, give `adam` exactly one LR callback next within `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`.","If `adam` is clearly worse or unstable at the matched reference recipe, keep `signum` and move to the next single-axis mainline recipe question before touching `K`.","Do not change loss, preprocess, or architecture until the optimizer branch is resolved cleanly on an accepted baseline."],"primary_variable":"optimizer"}
research/history/logs/agent_action_0074.json:1:{"command":"run","hypothesis":"Round 73 answered the optimizer question clearly: `adam` on the `two_stage_residual` reference recipe failed catastrophically (`FVU=33.8917`), so the optimizer branch should be considered closed and `signum` remains the correct mainline optimizer for this family. Following the prescribed order, the next single mainline question is now loss shaping: with `ARCHITECTURE=two_stage_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3` fixed, is the default auxiliary loss helping this staged residual decomposition, or does removing it improve the full training trajectory and final FVU?","summary":"Stay on the `two_stage_residual` mainline, return to the stable `signum` reference recipe, and change only the loss-side variable `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.03125` to `0.0`. Keep `ARCHITECTURE=two_stage_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3` fixed. Judge this run by the whole curve against the archived baseline, not just the endpoint: if dropping the auxiliary loss improves or smooths the trajectory, keep loss tuning alive; if it regresses or destabilizes training, restore the default loss and move to preprocess next.","change_type":"param_only","experiment_tier":"full","expected_win":"mainline_improvement","family_name":"two_stage_residual","family_stage":"mainline","self_review":"This stays on the active mainline family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, uses an allowed `K`, and changes exactly one primary variable: `loss`. It follows the required progression because the optimizer branch has now been cleanly falsified, so there is no justification for an optimizer-local LR callback. The main risk is that aux removal may have only a small effect, but it is the next policy-clean question before preprocess or any K movement.","needs_sanity":false,"env_overrides":[{"key":"ARCHITECTURE","value":"two_stage_residual"},{"key":"K","value":"128"},{"key":"EXPANSION_FACTOR","value":"12"},{"key":"OPTIMIZER","value":"signum"},{"key":"LR","value":"2.0e-3"},{"key":"BATCH_SIZE","value":"1"},{"key":"GRAD_ACC_STEPS","value":"8"},{"key":"MICRO_ACC_STEPS","value":"1"},{"key":"AUXK_ALPHA","value":"0.0"},{"key":"DEAD_FEATURE_THRESHOLD","value":"10000000"},{"key":"USE_HADAMARD","value":"0"}],"touched_files":[],"notes_to_memory":["Round 73 strongly rejected `adam` for `two_stage_residual` on the reference recipe, so the optimizer branch should be treated as closed and `signum` remains the mainline optimizer.","Round 74 should isolate the loss question on the stable `two_stage_residual@128` signum anchor by setting `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` at fixed `EF=12` and `LR=2.0e-3`, evaluating the whole curve rather than endpoint alone."],"next_hypotheses":["If `AUXK_ALPHA=0.0` improves the `two_stage_residual` curve or endpoint, keep loss-side tuning alive with at most one nearby confirmation.","If removing the auxiliary loss is clearly worse or unstable, restore the default loss and move to the preprocess question next.","If the effect is neutral, treat loss as mostly settled and proceed to preprocess before any K change."],"primary_variable":"loss"}
