research/history/round_summaries/round_0213.json:38:      "\u5982\u679c TRUNK_RANK=16 \u7684 FVU \u660e\u663e\u5d29\u584c\u6216\u8bad\u7ec3\u4ee3\u4ef7\u6ca1\u6709\u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u4f18\u52bf\uff0c\u5219\u8bf4\u660e lowrank_factorized_residual \u5728\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500\u533a\u4ecd\u8fc7\u5ea6\u4f9d\u8d56 trunk \u5bb9\u91cf\uff0c\u540e\u7eed\u5e94\u56de\u5230\u66f4\u77ed\u94fe\u8def family\u3002"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:7:  "family_name": "whitened_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:19:    "hypothesis": "With the `topk` mainline saturated for five rounds, the highest-value matched architecture probe is a directly compatible near-neighbor that changes support formation without changing the exported reconstruction form. `whitened_topk` keeps the same `K=128` sparse weighted-sum decoder contract as `topk` but adds input preconditioning before top-k competition, so this round asks one clean question: does that architectural change alone produce a meaningfully better curve or enough promise to justify follow-up work.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:20:    "summary": "Run one matched architecture probe on `whitened_topk`. Keep `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and the current stable non-compiled runtime/aux recipe fixed, and change only `ARCHITECTURE` from `topk` to `whitened_topk` to test whether this directly export-compatible variant is worth continuing as a family.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:23:    "family_name": "whitened_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:25:    "self_review": "This follows the Round 28 rule for a single matched architecture probe, changes exactly one primary variable (`architecture`), and chooses a candidate that remains close to LUTurbo's static-vector weighted-sum deployment contract. The main risk is that the preconditioning may add training complexity without improving reconstruction, but that is precisely the yes/no family-worthiness question this probe is meant to answer before returning to the mainline next round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:79:      "Round 28 inserts exactly one matched architecture probe after five consecutive non-improving topk rounds; the probe must be judged as a family-worthiness test, not as a new mainline pivot.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:80:      "`whitened_topk` is directly compatible with LUTurbo's deployment form because the final reconstruction remains a finite weighted sum over a static decoder library with fixed `K`; the architectural change is confined to encoder-side preconditioning and selection.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:81:      "Judge this probe by full curve shape plus final FVU relative to the stabilized K128 topk control: if it is clearly worse or unstable, drop the family and return to topk; if it is competitive or better, it earns at most one follow-up slot later, but the immediate next round should still return to the topk mainline."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:86:      "If `whitened_topk` beats the matched topk control, schedule exactly one later follow-up on the same family after the mandated return to the mainline."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:105:    "description": "Run one matched architecture probe on `whitened_topk`. Keep `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=1.6e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and the current stable non-compiled runtime/aux recipe fixed, and change only `ARCHITECTURE` from `topk` to `whitened_topk` to test whether this directly export-compatible variant is worth continuing as a family.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0028.json:106:    "self_review": "This follows the Round 28 rule for a single matched architecture probe, changes exactly one primary variable (`architecture`), and chooses a candidate that remains close to LUTurbo's static-vector weighted-sum deployment contract. The main risk is that the preconditioning may add training complexity without improving reconstruction, but that is precisely the yes/no family-worthiness question this probe is meant to answer before returning to the mainline next round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:7:  "family_name": "bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:18:    "summary": "Run one matched architecture probe on `bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual` with the mainline recipe unchanged otherwise. The family is LUTurbo-exportable (`\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`) via a static trunk library plus static codebook and residual dictionaries, but its matched EF=2 selector cost is expected to exceed budget (`~2.5x h\u00d7n`), so the likely result is a cheap policy rejection that cleanly answers: this architecture is not worth continuing as a low-cost mainline candidate right now.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:21:    "family_name": "bucketed_lowrank_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:22:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:23:    "self_review": "Single-variable discipline is preserved: architecture is the only changed dimension, while `K/EF/optimizer/LR` are pinned to the mainline recipe. I am choosing an intentionally decisive probe: it is informative even if rejected, because the low-EF budget constraint is now the main gate and this family is known to be runtime-heavier. This does not claim the family is universally bad; it only answers whether it is worth continuing on the current feasible low-cost frontier.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:50:      "At matched `K=128, EF=2`, the bucketed two-stage soft-codebook family estimates to about `selection_cost=2.5x` and is therefore over the `1.5x` hard budget; this makes it a likely fast policy-reject probe rather than a training candidate."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0175.json:54:      "If a future bucketed revisit is desired, only do it as a cost-reduction study on the bucketed family itself with primary variable `TRUNK_RANK` or `FACTORIZED_HIDDEN_DIM`, not as another matched-architecture probe."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:17:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe on `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` with `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=2`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=3.0e-3` fixed. Final reconstruction formula is `x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_m pi_m c_m + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i`, where `U(Vx)` is a static low-rank trunk library, `{c_m}` is a static soft-codebook library, and `{b_i}` is a static residual dictionary. This is `\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9`: LUTurbo/Lottable can export it as one static trunk lookup plus one static codebook lookup plus one sparse weighted sum over a static residual library, so inference remains a finite weighted sum over fixed vector banks. At EF=2 its encoder selection cost remains within the `\u2264 1.5\u00d7h\u00d7n` hard budget and below the current two-stage soft-codebook mainline. The single question is whether removing the second residual refinement stage preserves enough quality and runtime efficiency to justify continued attention as a cheaper compatible branch, or whether the second stage is clearly necessary.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:18:    "summary": "Run one valid matched architecture probe on `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` while keeping the `K=128`, `EF=2`, `signum`, `LR=3.0e-3` mainline recipe fixed. This cleanly tests whether the cheaper one-stage soft-codebook parent is still worth continued attention under LUTurbo-compatible low-EF constraints.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:21:    "family_name": "lowrank_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:22:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:23:    "self_review": "This obeys the single-variable rule by changing only `architecture` and explicitly pinning the current mainline recipe. The previous attempt on this family was policy-rejected rather than scientifically resolved, so the highest-value action is to rerun the same matched probe cleanly instead of opening another new family. `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` is the strongest cheaper compatible parent and directly tests whether the second sparse stage is actually earning its extra cost in the current deployable low-EF regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:55:      "If it is modestly worse in FVU but materially better in throughput or total runtime, keep it as a cheaper compatible Pareto branch, but still return to the mainline next round per probe policy.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0171.json:56:      "If it is unexpectedly very close to the mainline at lower selection cost, allow at most one later family-specific follow-up after the required return to the mainline."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Rounds 92 through 94 suggest the soft-codebook coarse branch is the first recent non-mainline idea with real signal, but the cheaper single-stage selectors (`lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`, `lowrank_grouped_soft_codebook_residual`, `lowrank_gated_soft_codebook_residual`) still did not beat the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor. The single most informative remaining matched architecture probe is `lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual`: it keeps the same LUTurbo-compatible static-library export path, but asks whether a front-loaded sparse budget after codebook projection can preserve most of the quality while shifting more of the work into the earlier coarse correction and reducing reliance on a large second-stage cleanup. This round answers one question only: under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, is that asymmetric soft-codebook two-stage architecture intrinsically worth any future follow-up, or should the soft-codebook branch be treated as unable to justify more complexity than the current mainline?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:23:    "family_name": "lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:52:      "Interpret this strictly as a family-worthiness test for whether the promising soft-codebook branch becomes more deployment-relevant when the sparse budget is front-loaded into the first refinement pass rather than split more evenly across two stages.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0095.json:53:      "Return to the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline next round regardless of outcome; do not open another new family immediately after this probe."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_factorized_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:8:  "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:17:    "hypothesis": "\u5019\u9009 family: lowrank_factorized_residual\u3002\u6700\u7ec8\u91cd\u6784\u516c\u5f0f\u4e3a x_hat = \u03a3_r beta_r u_r + \u03a3_i alpha_i b_i\uff0c\u5176\u4e2d {u_r} \u662f\u9759\u6001 trunk \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\u3001{b_i} \u662f\u9759\u6001 residual \u5411\u91cf\u5e93\uff1bfactorized scorer \u53ea\u5f71\u54cd\u5728\u7ebf\u9009\u62e9\u4e0e\u7cfb\u6570\u8ba1\u7b97\uff0c\u4e0d\u6539\u53d8 decoder \u7aef\u7684\u9759\u6001\u5e93\u6709\u9650\u52a0\u6743\u548c\u5f62\u5f0f\uff0c\u56e0\u6b64\u53ef\u5bfc\u51fa\u5230 LUTurbo/Lottable \u7684\u201c\u67e5\u8868 + \u52a0\u6743\u6c42\u548c + \u9009\u62e9\u6027\u8865\u507f\u201d\u94fe\u8def\uff0c\u517c\u5bb9\u6027\u4e3a\u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9\u3002\u5355\u4e3b\u53d8\u91cf\u9009\u62e9 TRUNK_RANK\uff1a\u5728\u4fdd\u6301 ARCHITECTURE=lowrank_factorized_residual\u3001K=64\u3001EF=1\u3001signum\u3001LR=3e-3 \u4e0d\u53d8\u65f6\uff0c\u628a trunk_rank \u4ece\u5f53\u524d auto\u2248128 \u4e0b\u8c03\u5230 32\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u5f53\u524d 0.69x \u70b9\u7684\u4e3b\u8981\u5197\u4f59\u662f\u5426\u6765\u81ea\u8fc7\u5927\u7684 trunk \u5e93\uff1b\u82e5 trunk \u53ea\u662f\u63d0\u4f9b\u7c97\u8865\u507f\u800c residual \u5206\u652f\u5df2\u627f\u62c5\u4e3b\u8981\u8868\u8fbe\uff0c\u5219\u53ef\u628a encoder+deployment \u603b\u6210\u672c\u4e00\u53e3\u6c14\u538b\u5165 <0.5x \u533a\u57df\uff0c\u540c\u65f6\u7ef4\u6301\u660e\u663e\u4f18\u4e8e topk@0.31x \u7684 FVU\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:21:    "family_name": "lowrank_factorized_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:22:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0212.json:57:      "\u5982\u679c TRUNK_RANK=32 \u4ecd\u4fdd\u6301\u660e\u663e\u4f18\u4e8e topk@EF1,K64 \u7684 FVU \u4e14\u8fdb\u5165 <0.5x\uff0c\u5219\u56fa\u5b9a\u8be5 family \u540e\u53ea\u6cbf K \u8f74\u505a\u4e00\u6b21\u8865\u70b9\u3002",
