research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:19:    "hypothesis": "After the plain, gated, JumpReLU, grouped, whitened, and factorized single-stage low-rank residual families all failed to challenge the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` K128 anchor, the most informative remaining matched architecture probe is `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual`. It preserves LUTurbo-compatible static-library export, but tests a different decomposition hypothesis: a coarse static codebook projection followed by one sparse residual correction may recover some of the mainline's quality without requiring a full second sparse residual stage. If this codebook-assisted single-stage family is still clearly weaker under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, then the current evidence favors true two-stage residual allocation over coarse-codebook-plus-single-stage alternatives.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:23:    "family_name": "lowrank_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the round policy by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping the mainline `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe fixed. `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` is a more informative remaining probe than another heavier multi-branch family because it still maps cleanly to static libraries and tests whether a coarse static branch can substitute for the second sparse residual pass. The main risk is that the extra codebook routing adds complexity without reducing LUTurbo online cost enough to matter, so this should be judged strictly as a family-worthiness screen.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:52:      "Judge this run strictly as a family-worthiness test for a coarse static codebook plus one sparse residual correction; the question is whether that decomposition can approach the mainline enough to justify any further attention.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:53:      "Return to the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline next round regardless of outcome; do not chain another new-family probe immediately after this one."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0092.json:77:    "self_review": "This obeys the round policy by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping the mainline `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe fixed. `lowrank_soft_codebook_residual` is a more informative remaining probe than another heavier multi-branch family because it still maps cleanly to static libraries and tests whether a coarse static branch can substitute for the second sparse residual pass. The main risk is that the extra codebook routing adds complexity without reducing LUTurbo online cost enough to matter, so this should be judged strictly as a family-worthiness screen.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:17:    "hypothesis": "Matched architecture probe under the fixed mainline recipe. Final reconstruction formula is x_hat = U(Vx) + \u03a3_m pi_m c_m + \u03a3_i alpha_i^(1) b_i + \u03a3_j alpha_j^(2) b_j, where the only structural change versus the current mainline is a front-loaded stage split with stage1_k\u22480.75K and stage2_k\u22480.25K. This is LUTurbo \u6269\u5c55\u517c\u5bb9 because the trunk term U(Vx), soft-codebook branch \u03a3_m pi_m c_m, and both residual sparse branches all decode from static vector libraries, so inference still exports to LUTurbo/Lottable as static lookup tables plus weighted sums plus optional residual compensation. The probe asks one question only: at K=128, EF=2, signum, LR=3.0e-3, is the asymmetric two-stage budget intrinsically better than the symmetric split enough to justify keeping this family alive?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:21:    "family_name": "lowrank_asymmetric_two_stage_soft_codebook_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:22:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:35:      "Feasibility check: this family stays within the 1.5x encoder selection-cost cap at EF=2, unlike routed/bucketed two-stage soft-codebook variants which would be over budget in the matched setting.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0200.json:40:      "If asymmetric two-stage again fails to beat the symmetric parent in the EF=2 feasible regime, mark this family not worth continuing."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:7:  "family_name": "lowrank_factorized_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:19:    "hypothesis": "`whitened_lowrank_residual` failed catastrophically at the matched K128 anchor, so the next matched architecture probe should avoid more whitening-style conditioning and instead test a different single-stage low-rank selector family. The most informative remaining probe is `lowrank_factorized_residual`: it preserves the low-rank trunk and static-library weighted-sum export path, but replaces the plain residual scorer with a factorized scorer. This answers one clean question: can a more structured single-stage selector recover enough of the two-stage mainline's quality to be worth continuing, or is the second residual stage itself the essential ingredient. If `lowrank_factorized_residual` is still clearly weaker under the exact matched `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe, then the remaining single-stage low-rank selector variants are likely not worth further follow-up in the current regime.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:23:    "family_name": "lowrank_factorized_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the round policy by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping the mainline `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe fixed. I am explicitly avoiding `lowrank_adaptive_budget_residual` because with the current batch-size-1 regime it collapses to ordinary top-k behavior and would not be an informative matched probe. The main risk is that `lowrank_factorized_residual` may add selector complexity without helping quality or LUTurbo online cost, so this should be judged strictly as a yes/no family-worthiness test before returning to the mainline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:53:      "Judge this run strictly as a family-worthiness test for a structured single-stage low-rank selector; return to the `lowrank_two_stage_residual` mainline next round regardless of outcome."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0091.json:77:    "self_review": "This obeys the round policy by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping the mainline `K=128`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, and `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` recipe fixed. I am explicitly avoiding `lowrank_adaptive_budget_residual` because with the current batch-size-1 regime it collapses to ordinary top-k behavior and would not be an informative matched probe. The main risk is that `lowrank_factorized_residual` may add selector complexity without helping quality or LUTurbo online cost, so this should be judged strictly as a yes/no family-worthiness test before returning to the mainline.",
