research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:8:  "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 56 answered the loss question on the strengthened `gated` recipe cleanly enough: removing the auxiliary term finished essentially flat-to-worse (`0.142968` vs the `0.142923` anchor), so the mainline recipe remains `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. With LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess now all re-checked on the active family, the next single question in the prescribed order is back on the K axis: if we keep the finalized `gated` recipe fixed and reduce only `K` from `128` to `96`, does the lower-cost point still reproduce a healthy full training curve under the now-settled mainline recipe, or was the earlier `K=96` result partly specific to an intermediate recipe-validation phase?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:20:    "summary": "Stay on the active `gated` family and hold the now-settled mainline recipe fixed at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Change only `K` from `128` to `96` to refresh the first lower-cost deployment point under the finalized recipe. Judge this run by the whole trajectory, not just terminal FVU: if the curve remains smooth and lands near or below the current `gated@96` frontier (`0.160940`), then the strengthened recipe is stable enough to treat that lower-cost point as a reliable LUTurbo candidate; if it degrades materially, re-open the question of whether the prior K sweep depended on transient recipe-state rather than the settled mainline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the same family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `k`. It also follows the required sequencing: the mainline recipe has now been re-localized on LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess, so returning to K is the clean next step. The main risk is spending a round on confirmation rather than frontier expansion, but after four consecutive non-improving recipe probes the most useful next question is whether the first lower-cost operating point is stable under the finalized recipe rather than only under the earlier sweep context.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:104:    "description": "Stay on the active `gated` family and hold the now-settled mainline recipe fixed at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, and `USE_HADAMARD=1`. Change only `K` from `128` to `96` to refresh the first lower-cost deployment point under the finalized recipe. Judge this run by the whole trajectory, not just terminal FVU: if the curve remains smooth and lands near or below the current `gated@96` frontier (`0.160940`), then the strengthened recipe is stable enough to treat that lower-cost point as a reliable LUTurbo candidate; if it degrades materially, re-open the question of whether the prior K sweep depended on transient recipe-state rather than the settled mainline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0057.json:105:    "self_review": "This stays on the same family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `k`. It also follows the required sequencing: the mainline recipe has now been re-localized on LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess, so returning to K is the clean next step. The main risk is spending a round on confirmation rather than frontier expansion, but after four consecutive non-improving recipe probes the most useful next question is whether the first lower-cost operating point is stable under the finalized recipe rather than only under the earlier sweep context.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:8:  "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:20:    "summary": "Stay on the active `gated` family and return to the `signum` anchor at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3`, with the same runtime knobs pinned, and change only the loss-side variable `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.03125` to `0.0`. Judge this run by curve shape as well as terminal FVU: if dropping aux yields a smoother or lower full trajectory than the current `0.148156` anchor, then the stronger LR has made the auxiliary term unnecessary or harmful; if it regresses or destabilizes training, keep the default aux loss and move on to preprocess.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:25:    "self_review": "This keeps the search on the same family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one non-core variable after the optimizer branch was cleanly falsified twice. I am not spending another round on Adam LR because the updated `adam` trial was not borderline or merely mistuned; it repeated the same qualitative failure pattern and got worse at the stronger anchor. The main risk is that aux removal may have only a small effect, but it is now the next most policy-clean question before preprocess or K movement.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:104:    "description": "Stay on the active `gated` family and return to the `signum` anchor at `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3`, with the same runtime knobs pinned, and change only the loss-side variable `AUXK_ALPHA` from `0.03125` to `0.0`. Judge this run by curve shape as well as terminal FVU: if dropping aux yields a smoother or lower full trajectory than the current `0.148156` anchor, then the stronger LR has made the auxiliary term unnecessary or harmful; if it regresses or destabilizes training, keep the default aux loss and move on to preprocess.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0042.json:105:    "self_review": "This keeps the search on the same family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one non-core variable after the optimizer branch was cleanly falsified twice. I am not spending another round on Adam LR because the updated `adam` trial was not borderline or merely mistuned; it repeated the same qualitative failure pattern and got worse at the stronger anchor. The main risk is that aux removal may have only a small effect, but it is now the next most policy-clean question before preprocess or K movement.",
