research/history/round_summaries/round_0216.json:53:      "\u5982\u679c K224 \u7684\u6536\u76ca\u5df2\u660e\u663e\u53d8\u5c0f\u6216\u8bad\u7ec3\u4ee3\u4ef7\u5f00\u59cb\u6076\u5316\uff0c\u5219\u8bf4\u660e EF=1 \u4e0b\u7ee7\u7eed\u5806 K \u7684\u8fb9\u9645\u6536\u76ca\u63a5\u8fd1\u8017\u5c3d\uff0c\u540e\u7eed\u5e94\u8f6c\u5411\u65b0\u7684\u4f4e\u6210\u672c family\u3002"
research/history/round_summaries/round_0216.json:73:    "description": "\u7ee7\u7eed\u4f7f\u7528\u76f4\u63a5\u517c\u5bb9\u7684 topk family\uff0c\u56fa\u5b9a EF=1\u3001signum\u3001LR=3e-3\uff0c\u628a K \u63d0\u5230 224\uff0c\u6d4b\u8bd5\u662f\u5426\u80fd\u5728\u4ecd\u4f4e\u4e8e 0.5x \u603b\u6210\u672c\u7684\u524d\u63d0\u4e0b\uff0c\u628a\u4f4e\u5f00\u9500\u533a\u6700\u4f73 FVU \u4ece 0.1635 \u8fdb\u4e00\u6b65\u538b\u4f4e\u3002",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:7:  "family_name": "factorized_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:19:    "hypothesis": "After the matched `topk` probe came back only slightly worse than the strengthened `gated` anchor, the next highest-value single architecture question is whether a simpler export-compatible scoring path can retain most of the quality while offering a cheaper route for online selection and coefficient computation. `factorized_topk` keeps the same static-dictionary finite weighted-sum reconstruction form as `topk/gated`, but replaces direct latent scoring with a low-rank mixing stage before top-k selection, so this round asks one clean yes/no question: under the exact current mainline recipe (`K=128`, `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`), is `factorized_topk` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to justify any later follow-up as a LUTurbo-oriented family?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:23:    "family_name": "factorized_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 59 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the settled mainline recipe fixed. `factorized_topk` is a stronger LUTurbo-oriented probe than opening another heavier residual family because it preserves the same export contract while plausibly reducing support-scoring complexity; the main risk is that reusing the `gated`-tuned recipe understates its ceiling, but that is acceptable for a family-worthiness screen.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:79:      "Round 58 showed that matched `topk` under the strengthened `gated` recipe is only modestly worse (`0.146999` vs `0.142923`), so simpler export-compatible architectures remain worth probing when the `gated` mainline stalls.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:80:      "`factorized_topk` remains LUTurbo-compatible because the final reconstruction is still a finite weighted sum over a static decoder library with fixed `K`; the architectural change is confined to a low-rank scoring stage before top-k support selection.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:81:      "Round 59 should judge `factorized_topk` purely as a family-worthiness probe against the current `gated@128` anchor: if it is clearly worse or unstable, archive it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, keep exactly one later follow-up slot available."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:86:      "If matched `factorized_topk` unexpectedly beats the current `gated` anchor, return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy but schedule exactly one later follow-up for this family."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0059.json:106:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 59 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the settled mainline recipe fixed. `factorized_topk` is a stronger LUTurbo-oriented probe than opening another heavier residual family because it preserves the same export contract while plausibly reducing support-scoring complexity; the main risk is that reusing the `gated`-tuned recipe understates its ceiling, but that is acceptable for a family-worthiness screen.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:7:  "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:19:    "hypothesis": "With the `gated` mainline now stable but non-improving for five rounds, the highest-value single matched architecture probe is the simplest directly compatible alternative: `topk`. It preserves LUTurbo's static-vector finite weighted-sum export form while potentially lowering online selection and coefficient cost relative to `gated`, so this round asks one clean yes/no question: under the exact current mainline recipe (`K=128`, `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`), is `topk` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to be worth revisiting as a family, or does `gated` remain clearly superior even before runtime considerations are counted?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:20:    "summary": "Run one matched architecture probe on `topk`. Keep the current mainline recipe fixed at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`, and the same runtime knobs, and change only `ARCHITECTURE` from `gated` to `topk`. Judge this probe by the whole trajectory, not just the endpoint: if `topk` stays smooth and closes most of the gap to the `0.142923` `gated` anchor, it is still worth later family-level consideration because its deployment path is simpler; if it is clearly worse across the curve, archive it as a non-promising matched alternative and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:23:    "family_name": "topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 58 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the rest of the settled mainline recipe fixed. `topk` is the best probe candidate because it remains directly export-compatible for LUTurbo and offers a simpler online path than `gated`; the main risk is that reusing the `gated`-tuned recipe may understate topk's ceiling, but that is acceptable here because this round is explicitly a family-worthiness screen, not a new topk tuning campaign.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:79:      "Round 58 is a single matched architecture probe inserted after five consecutive non-improving `gated` rounds; it must be judged only as a family-worthiness test, and the next round should return to the `gated` mainline regardless of outcome.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:80:      "`topk` is directly compatible with LUTurbo deployment because the reconstruction remains a finite weighted sum over a static decoder library with fixed `K`; compared with `gated`, it may also lower online selection and coefficient-computation cost if quality remains competitive.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:106:    "description": "Run one matched architecture probe on `topk`. Keep the current mainline recipe fixed at `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, `OPTIMIZER=signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`, and the same runtime knobs, and change only `ARCHITECTURE` from `gated` to `topk`. Judge this probe by the whole trajectory, not just the endpoint: if `topk` stays smooth and closes most of the gap to the `0.142923` `gated` anchor, it is still worth later family-level consideration because its deployment path is simpler; if it is clearly worse across the curve, archive it as a non-promising matched alternative and return to the `gated` mainline next round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0058.json:107:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 58 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the rest of the settled mainline recipe fixed. `topk` is the best probe candidate because it remains directly export-compatible for LUTurbo and offers a simpler online path than `gated`; the main risk is that reusing the `gated`-tuned recipe may understate topk's ceiling, but that is acceptable here because this round is explicitly a family-worthiness screen, not a new topk tuning campaign.",
