research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 71 showed that `two_stage_residual` can benefit modestly from a higher `signum` learning rate, but Round 72 was policy-rejected because it tried to combine the optimizer test with that LR shift in a single `param_only` move. The next single mainline question remains the optimizer question, and it must be isolated cleanly from the archived reference recipe: with `ARCHITECTURE=two_stage_residual`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=2.0e-3` fixed, does switching `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam` produce a healthier curve or competitive final FVU, or does this family still clearly prefer `signum`?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:23:    "family_name": "two_stage_residual",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active mainline family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, uses an allowed `K`, and changes exactly one primary variable: `optimizer`. It directly fixes the Round 72 policy failure by reverting to the current mainline reference recipe instead of carrying forward the `LR=2.4e-3` adjustment into the optimizer test. The tradeoff is that this tests `adam` against the conservative anchor rather than the best observed signum LR, but that is the only policy-clean way to isolate the optimizer branch this round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0073.json:102:    "self_review": "This stays on the active mainline family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, uses an allowed `K`, and changes exactly one primary variable: `optimizer`. It directly fixes the Round 72 policy failure by reverting to the current mainline reference recipe instead of carrying forward the `LR=2.4e-3` adjustment into the optimizer test. The tradeoff is that this tests `adam` against the conservative anchor rather than the best observed signum LR, but that is the only policy-clean way to isolate the optimizer branch this round.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:7:  "family_name": "codebook_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:23:    "family_name": "codebook_topk",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 77 rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, and the rest of the recipe fixed. `codebook_topk` is a better use of the single probe than revisiting already-rejected plain selector variants because it tests a different cost-quality tradeoff that is still compatible with LUTurbo's static export contract. The main risk is that prior matched probing in an earlier regime already suggested weakness, but this remains the most informative remaining architecture-worthiness check under the current mainline anchor.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:76:      "Judge this probe as a family-worthiness test only: compare matched `codebook_topk@128` against the `two_stage_residual` reference at fixed `EF=12`, `signum`, and `LR=2.0e-3`, then return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round regardless of outcome."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:81:      "If matched `codebook_topk` unexpectedly beats the current `two_stage_residual` reference, still return to the `two_stage_residual` mainline next round per policy, but record `codebook_topk` as a high-priority later follow-up family."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0077.json:102:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 77 rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, and the rest of the recipe fixed. `codebook_topk` is a better use of the single probe than revisiting already-rejected plain selector variants because it tests a different cost-quality tradeoff that is still compatible with LUTurbo's static export contract. The main risk is that prior matched probing in an earlier regime already suggested weakness, but this remains the most informative remaining architecture-worthiness check under the current mainline anchor.",
