research/history/round_summaries/round_0034.json:19:    "hypothesis": "With the `gated` mainline anchored back at `K=128, EF=12, optimizer=signum, lr=1.6e-3`, adding a small auxiliary sparsity-support loss via `auxk_alpha=0.03125` may improve training dynamics without changing the family or optimizer; this round asks only whether a light loss-shaping term reduces plateauing and yields a better full-curve profile than the plain baseline.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0034.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0034.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0034.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the same family, keeps EF fixed at 12, does not touch K, and changes exactly one main variable: `auxk_alpha`. It also respects the prescribed order by moving to a loss-side probe only after the basic LR and optimizer checks have not yielded an improvement.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0034.json:81:    "self_review": "This stays on the same family, keeps EF fixed at 12, does not touch K, and changes exactly one main variable: `auxk_alpha`. It also respects the prescribed order by moving to a loss-side probe only after the basic LR and optimizer checks have not yielded an improvement.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:8:  "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:20:    "summary": "Keep the active `gated` family and move to the optimizer axis now that the LR sweep has identified `2.0e-3` as the best current signum setting. Run `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=2.0e-3` with all reference aux/runtime knobs explicitly pinned, and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`. Judge the result by the whole trajectory, not just endpoint: if `adam` descends more cleanly or closes the gap at the stronger `2.0e-3` anchor, it earns exactly one LR callback next; if it is flatter, noisier, or clearly worse again, lock `signum` as the gated optimizer and stop the optimizer branch.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the same mainline family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one core variable: `optimizer`. It follows the stated round order after the LR branch produced a modest win at `2.0e-3` and a slight regression at `2.4e-3`, which is enough evidence to stop spending more rounds on signum LR micro-tuning before checking optimizer. The main risk is that `adam` was already poor at `1.6e-3`, but that makes this a bounded confirmation rather than an open-ended sweep.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:104:    "description": "Keep the active `gated` family and move to the optimizer axis now that the LR sweep has identified `2.0e-3` as the best current signum setting. Run `ARCHITECTURE=gated`, `K=128`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12`, and `LR=2.0e-3` with all reference aux/runtime knobs explicitly pinned, and change only `OPTIMIZER` from `signum` to `adam`. Judge the result by the whole trajectory, not just endpoint: if `adam` descends more cleanly or closes the gap at the stronger `2.0e-3` anchor, it earns exactly one LR callback next; if it is flatter, noisier, or clearly worse again, lock `signum` as the gated optimizer and stop the optimizer branch.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0041.json:105:    "self_review": "This stays on the same mainline family, respects the fixed `EF=12` rule, and changes exactly one core variable: `optimizer`. It follows the stated round order after the LR branch produced a modest win at `2.0e-3` and a slight regression at `2.4e-3`, which is enough evidence to stop spending more rounds on signum LR micro-tuning before checking optimizer. The main risk is that `adam` was already poor at `1.6e-3`, but that makes this a bounded confirmation rather than an open-ended sweep.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:7:  "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:8:  "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 46 answered the `K=64` transfer question positively: the strengthened `gated` recipe (`signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`) did not merely hold up, it materially improved the prior `gated@64` result and now owns the frontier at that support. The next single question is where this downward transfer breaks for LUTurbo-relevant cost reduction: if we keep the same improved recipe fixed and reduce only `K` to `32`, does `gated` remain competitive enough to establish a stronger lower-cost point, or does the family advantage collapse below the high-K regime?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:23:    "family_name": "gated",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:24:    "family_stage": "mainline",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:25:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `gated` family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `K`. It follows the current mainline logic because the clean baseline, LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess questions have already been resolved on this recipe, and the last two rounds showed successful transfer from `K=128` to `K=96` and then to `K=64`. The main risk is that `K=32` may sit beyond the range where the improved gating recipe is effective, but that is precisely the highest-value remaining single-variable question for mapping LUTurbo-relevant cost-quality tradeoffs.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0047.json:105:    "self_review": "This stays on the active `gated` family, respects the fixed `EXPANSION_FACTOR=12` rule, and changes exactly one primary variable: `K`. It follows the current mainline logic because the clean baseline, LR, optimizer, loss, and preprocess questions have already been resolved on this recipe, and the last two rounds showed successful transfer from `K=128` to `K=96` and then to `K=64`. The main risk is that `K=32` may sit beyond the range where the improved gating recipe is effective, but that is precisely the highest-value remaining single-variable question for mapping LUTurbo-relevant cost-quality tradeoffs.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:7:  "family_name": "routed",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:8:  "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:19:    "hypothesis": "Round 60 showed that matched `jumprelu` is competitive enough to avoid immediate dismissal but still clearly trails the strengthened `gated` anchor (`0.148243` vs `0.142923`), so the next single architecture question should test the closest support-selection near-neighbor rather than another looser variant. `routed` preserves LUTurbo's static-vector finite weighted-sum reconstruction contract while separating support routing from activation magnitude, so this round asks one clean yes/no question: under the exact current mainline recipe (`K=128`, `EF=12`, `signum`, `LR=2.0e-3`, `AUXK_ALPHA=0.03125`, `USE_HADAMARD=1`), is `routed` competitive enough in full-curve behavior to justify any later follow-up as a deployment-relevant family?",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:23:    "family_name": "routed",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:24:    "family_stage": "prototype",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:25:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 61 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the settled mainline recipe fixed. `routed` is the highest-value remaining probe because it stays very close to the successful `gated` family while changing only the support-selection mechanism, which is directly relevant to LUTurbo online cost. The main risk is that the matched `gated`-tuned recipe may not be ideal for routed support, but that is acceptable for a family-worthiness screen.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:80:      "`routed` remains LUTurbo-compatible because the reconstruction is still a finite weighted sum over a static decoder library with fixed `K`; the architectural change is confined to using a separate router for support selection while preserving the same export form.",
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:81:      "Round 61 should judge `routed` purely as a family-worthiness probe against the current `gated@128` anchor: if it is clearly worse or unstable, archive it and return to the `gated` mainline next round; if it is competitive, keep exactly one later follow-up slot available."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:86:      "If matched `routed` unexpectedly beats the current `gated` anchor, return to the `gated` mainline next round per policy but schedule exactly one later follow-up for this family."
research/history/round_summaries/round_0061.json:106:    "self_review": "This obeys the Round 61 matched-probe rule by changing exactly one primary variable, `architecture`, while keeping `K`, `OPTIMIZER`, `LR`, `EXPANSION_FACTOR`, and the settled mainline recipe fixed. `routed` is the highest-value remaining probe because it stays very close to the successful `gated` family while changing only the support-selection mechanism, which is directly relevant to LUTurbo online cost. The main risk is that the matched `gated`-tuned recipe may not be ideal for routed support, but that is acceptable for a family-worthiness screen.",
